    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-05-06T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-05-06T12:00:00-05:00" n="457"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d457">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.24/907: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Standley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-06T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 6, 1942—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>199. Personal for the Ambassador. The President has asked me to send you for your
                    information the following message, which he yesterday asked Ambassador Litvinov
                    to transmit direct to Mr. Stalin:<note n="3" xml:id="d457fn3">The original copy
                        of the telegram was dated May 4, 1942.</note>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Grave difficulties are being met in the northern convoy route and
                            Litvinov has been advised regarding the complications.<note n="4"
                                xml:id="d457fn4">Regarding the difficulties encountered at that time
                                on the northern convoy route, see telegram No. 144, May 7, from the
                                Second Secretary of Embassy in the Soviet Union, and footnote 84,
                                    <ref target="#pg_701">p. 701</ref>.</note> I want to <pb
                                facs="0560" n="554" xml:id="pg_554"/> assure you, however, that we
                            shall omit no effort in sending off the greatest possible number of
                            ships. I want to express my appreciation to you for your cordial
                            reception of Admiral Standley, of which I have been told.</p>
                        <p>As soon as I know of the route which will be taken by Molotov, whom I
                            look forward to seeing, we shall undertake to provide and prepare
                            immediate transportation for him. I earnestly hope that he can stay at
                            the White House with me while he is here, but if it is desired, we can
                            make available a private home which will be nearby. Roosevelt.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
